  "copy": {
    "caption": "Cube poop, rock-hard bottom, and an underground palace.",
    "shortDescription": "Wombats are stocky, powerful Australian marsupials that dig elaborate burrow systems with their strong claws and flattened head. Their pouch opens backward — facing the tail rather than the head — so dirt doesn't pour in while they're digging. When a predator chases them into a burrow, wombats use their thick, tough bottom to block the entrance like a living trapdoor — the predator simply cannot get past. Fun fact: Wombats are the only animals in the world known to produce cube-shaped droppings."
